<main id="content" class="content"> <header> <h1 class="title">The Fourteenth Sunday After Pentecost</h1>
 <p class="subtitle" role="doc-subtitle">Jan 13, 2015 00:00</p>
</header> <p>
I love it when a minister points out something that I had never noticed in the text. Mitch Randall certainly did that this past Sunday. So, this prayer recalls Danielâ€™s action to save his competitors in Babylon as recounted in Daniel 2.
</p>

 <p>
If there is to be a winner, <br></br>
there must be a loser. <br></br>
or so it goes in the games we play, <br></br>
in games of sport, <br></br>
and in games of life.
</p>

 <p>
The clever person ensures success <br></br>
by eliminating the competition.
</p>

 <p>
Guns and knives are too crude <br></br>
for our sophisticated times, <br></br>
instead we use words <br></br>
to harm reputations <br></br>
and rumors to destroy characters.
</p>

 <p>
And then, in the end, <br></br>
we can rest content <br></br>
in victory, <br></br>
isolated and alone.
</p>

 <p>
Lord,
</p>

 <p>
Bid us again <br></br>
to play in your fields, <br></br>
where contact is <br></br>
not hand-to-hand, <br></br>
but hand-in-hand.
</p>

 <p>
 <i>Amen</i>
</p>


